[{"category":"section","location":"reference/#Reference","page":"Reference","text":"","title":"Reference"},{"category":"module","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.DiagHamInterface","page":"Reference","text":"Interface to the DiagHam library.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.DiagHamInterface"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.density_density_to_two_body_normal-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Array{T, 12}, Array{T, 6}}} where T","page":"Reference","text":"density_density_to_two_body_normal(rho_dd, rho1; statistics=:fermi) -> Array{T,12}\n\nConvert the density-density ordering ⟨c†_1 c_3 c†_2 c_4⟩ back to the normal-ordered two-body density matrix ⟨c†_1 c†_2 c_3 c_4⟩.\n\nFor fermions: ⟨c†_1 c†_2 c_3 c_4⟩ = δ_{23} ⟨c†_1 c_4⟩ - ⟨c†_1 c_3 c†_2 c_4⟩ For bosons:   ⟨b†_1 b†_2 b_3 b_4⟩ = δ_{23} ⟨b†_1 b_4⟩ + ⟨b†_1 b_3 b†_2 b_4⟩\n\nrho_dd has index semantics [k1,b1,s1, k3,b3,s3, k2,b2,s2, k4,b4,s4] as returned by two_body_normal_to_density_density. The returned array has the same shape with index semantics [k1,b1,s1, k2,b2,s2, k3,b3,s3, k4,b4,s4].\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.density_density_to_two_body_normal"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.diagham_command-Tuple{AbstractString}","page":"Reference","text":"diagham_command(execute; kwargs...)\n\nConstruct a command string for running a DiagHam executable with specified kwargs as CLI flags.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.diagham_command"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.execute_diagham_script-Tuple{AbstractString}","page":"Reference","text":"execute_diagham_script(execute; kwargs...)\n\nRun a DiagHam executable. Kwargs are converted to CLI flags (_ → -). Single-char keys use -k, multi-char use --key. Boolean true adds flag, false omits.\n\nThe kwargs of Cmd() and run() are supported.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.execute_diagham_script"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.fix_fileending-Tuple{AbstractString, AbstractString}","page":"Reference","text":"fix_fileending(filename, ending)\n\nReturn filename ensuring it ends with ending.\n\nIf ending does not start with a dot, a dot is prepended. If ending is empty, the original filename is returned. The function is safe to call with full paths; it only checks the final characters of filename.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.fix_fileending"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.format_with_precision-Tuple{T} where T<:Real","page":"Reference","text":"format_with_precision(x; atol=eps(float(T)), maxdigits=typemax(Int))\n\nFormat number x as a string with absolute precision atol and a maximum of  maxdigits significant digits.  Uses scientific notation for very small or large numbers.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.format_with_precision"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.get_diagham_path-Tuple{}","page":"Reference","text":"get_diagham_path()\n\nGet the current path to the DiagHam build directory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.get_diagham_path"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.install_diagham-Tuple{}","page":"Reference","text":"install_diagham(; source_dir, build_dir=nothing, run_dir=nothing, configure_options=[\"--enable-fqhe\",\"--enable-fti\",\"--with-blas-libs=-lopenblas\",\"--with-lapack-libs=\",\"--enable-lapack\"])\n\nCheckout and build DiagHam from source. Returns the path to the build directory.\n\nParameters are keyword-only and intended to be easily overridden from tests or user code.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.install_diagham"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.read_matrix_from_txt-Tuple{String}","page":"Reference","text":"read_matrix_from_txt(filename; sparsity=0.1)\n\nRead Hamiltonian from DiagHam-format text file. Auto-detects real/complex. Returns dense matrix if non-zero fraction > sparsity, else sparse.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.read_matrix_from_txt"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.read_one_body_density-Tuple{AbstractString}","page":"Reference","text":"read_one_body_density(filename; atol=1e-14) -> Array{T,6}\n\nRead a one-body density matrix file produced by DiagHam's FTIDensity program.\n\nReturns an array of shape (Nk, Nband, Nspin, Nk, Nband, Nspin) where result[k1, b1, s1, k2, b2, s2] = ⟨c†_{k1-1, b1-1, s1-1} c_{k2-1, b2-1, s2-1}⟩.\n\nThe momentum index k is linearized as k = kx*Nky + ky (0-based in file, 1-based in the returned array). Nkx, Nky, Nband, Nspin are inferred from the data. For single-band files Nband=1 and Nspin=1. For files with a spin column (NbrBands=4 or 6) Nspin=2.\n\nSince FTIDensity only writes diagonal-in-k entries, all off-diagonal-k entries are zero.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.read_one_body_density"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.read_two_body_density-Tuple{AbstractString}","page":"Reference","text":"read_two_body_density(filename; atol=1e-14) -> Array{T,12}\n\nRead a two-body density matrix file produced by DiagHam's FTIDensity program (output of the --rhorho flag).\n\nReturns an array of shape (Nk,Nb,Ns, Nk,Nb,Ns, Nk,Nb,Ns, Nk,Nb,Ns) where result[k1,b1,s1, k2,b2,s2, k3,b3,s3, k4,b4,s4] = ⟨c†_1 c†_2 c_3 c_4⟩. All indices are 1-based; k is linearized as k = kx*Nky + ky + 1.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.read_two_body_density"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.set_diagham_path-Tuple{Any}","page":"Reference","text":"set_diagham_path(path)\n\nSet the path to the DiagHam build directory.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.set_diagham_path"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.two_body_normal_to_density_density-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{Array{T, 12}, Array{T, 6}}} where T","page":"Reference","text":"two_body_normal_to_density_density(rho2, rho1; statistics=:fermi) -> Array{T,12}\n\nConvert the normal-ordered two-body density matrix ⟨c†_1 c†_2 c_3 c_4⟩ to the density-density ordering ⟨c†_1 c_3 c†_2 c_4⟩ using commutation relations.\n\nFor fermions (statistics=:fermi, anticommutator {c,c†}=δ):     ⟨c†1 c3 c†2 c4⟩ = δ{23} ⟨c†1 c4⟩ - ⟨c†1 c†2 c3 c_4⟩\n\nFor bosons (statistics=:bose, commutator [b,b†]=δ):     ⟨b†1 b3 b†2 b4⟩ = δ{23} ⟨b†1 b4⟩ + ⟨b†1 b†2 b3 b_4⟩\n\nrho2 has shape (Nk,Nb,Ns, Nk,Nb,Ns, Nk,Nb,Ns, Nk,Nb,Ns) (from read_two_body_density). rho1 has shape (Nk,Nb,Ns, Nk,Nb,Ns) (from read_one_body_density). The returned array has the same shape as rho2, with index semantics [k1,b1,s1, k3,b3,s3, k2,b2,s2, k4,b4,s4].\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.two_body_normal_to_density_density"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.write_matrix_elements-Tuple{Any, Any, Any, String}","page":"Reference","text":"write_matrix_elements(label, indices, coeffs, file_name; dropband=false, full_single_particle=false)\n\nWrite matrix elements to DiagHam-format file with header and data rows. dropband=true removes band index for single-band data. full_single_particle=true keeps both band indices for one-body terms.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.write_matrix_elements"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.write_to_txt-Tuple{SparseArrays.SparseMatrixCSC, String}","page":"Reference","text":"Optimized write_to_txt for SparseMatrixCSC. Converts to CSR internally.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.write_to_txt"},{"category":"method","location":"reference/#DiagHamInterface.write_to_txt-Union{Tuple{T}, Tuple{AbstractMatrix{T}, String}} where T<:Number","page":"Reference","text":"write_to_txt(Ham, filename; atol)\n\nWrite Hamiltonian matrix to DiagHam-format text file (sparse coordinate format, 0-based indexing). Elements with abs(val) ≤ atol are omitted. Existing files are backed up.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"DiagHamInterface.write_to_txt"},{"category":"section","location":"index/#Index","page":"Index","text":"","title":"Index"},{"category":"section","location":"#DiagHamInterface.jl","page":"Home","text":"DiagHamInterface.jl is a Julia package that provides an interface to DiagHam, a suite of exact diagonalization programs for quantum many-body systems.","title":"DiagHamInterface.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Installation","page":"Home","text":"The package is not yet registered in the Julia general registry. It can be installed trough the package manager with the following command:\n\npkg> add git@github.com:ManyBodyLab/DiagHamInterface.jl.git","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Code-Samples","page":"Home","text":"julia> using DiagHamInterface\njulia> open(\"pseudopotentials.dat\", \"w\") do io\n           write(io, \"Pseudopotentials = 0.0 1.0 \\n\")\n       end\njulia> execute_diagham_script(\n           \"FQHE/src/Programs/FQHEOnTorus/FQHETorusFermionsTwoBodyGeneric\";\n           p = 3,        # Number of particles\n           l = 9,        # Number of flux quanta (N_phi = p * q = 3 * 3 = 9 for 1/3 filling)\n           interaction_file = \"pseudopotentials.dat\",\n           interaction_name = \"V1\",\n       )\njulia> A = rand(ComplexF64,100, 100); Ham = A' * A; # Create a random positive definite Hamiltonian\njulia> write_to_txt(A, \"hamiltonian.txt\") # Write Hamiltonian to text file\njulia> execute_diagham_script(\n           \"src/Programs/GenericHamiltonianDiagonalization\";\n           c = true,\n           data_columns = 2,\n           use_lapack = true,\n           hamiltonian = \"hamiltonian.txt\",\n           o = \"spectrum.txt\",\n           all_eigenstates = true,\n           eigenstate_file = \"eigenstates.txt\",\n       )","title":"Code Samples"},{"category":"section","location":"#License","page":"Home","text":"DiagHamInterface.jl is licensed under the APL2 License. By using or interacting with this software in any way, you agree to the license of this software.\n\n\n\nThis page was generated using Literate.jl.","title":"License"}]
